ğŸ”¹ Indirect Expansion in Bash (${!var})
Indirect expansion means:
ğŸ‘‰ You have a variable that stores the name of another variable, and you want to get the value of that other variable.

1. Basic Example
name="Rakesh"
var="name"
echo $var      # name     (just the string)
echo ${!var}   # Rakesh   (value of variable "name")
$var â†’ expands to "name"
${!var} â†’ expands to value of $name â†’ "Rakesh"

2. Useful with Dynamic Variable Names
Sometimes variable names are generated dynamically.
server1="192.168.1.10"
server2="192.168.1.11"
id=2
echo ${!server$id}   # expands to ${!server2} â†’ 192.168.1.11

3. Array Index Indirection
arr[0]="apple"
arr[1]="banana"
index=1
echo ${arr[$index]}   # banana
âš ï¸ But if you store "arr[1]" inside another variable:
ref="arr[1]"
echo ${!ref}   # banana

4. Indirect Expansion with Prefix Matching
${!prefix*} and ${!prefix@} â†’ list all variable names that start with a prefix.
db_user="admin"
db_pass="secret"
db_host="localhost"
echo ${!db*}   # db_user db_pass db_host

5. Common Use-Cases
âœ… Dynamic configuration loading
âœ… Looping over variables with numbered suffixes (var1, var2, â€¦)
âœ… Avoiding eval (safer & cleaner)
âš¡ Example: Loop over numbered vars
for i in 1 2
do
   var="server$i"
   echo "Server $i: ${!var}"
done
ğŸ‘‰ In short:
$var = value of variable var
${!var} = value of the variable whose name is stored in var

6. Nameref (declare -n) (Bash â‰¥ 4.3)
Creates a reference variable (like a pointer in C).
Changes through nameref affect the original variable.
Syntax:
name="Rakesh"
declare -n ref=name
echo $ref      # Rakesh
ref="Kumar"    # modifies 'name'
echo $name     # Kumar
Advantages:
âœ… Works for both read and write
âœ… Cleaner with arrays and functions
âœ… Avoids complex ${!var} nesting
